<worksheet xml:id="activity-tutorial-5">
  <title>Tutorial-5</title>
  <introduction>
                <p>
                    Following exercises are taken from Section 13.5 of the book <em>Abstract Algebra</em> by Dummit and Foote.
                </p>
  </introduction>
  <page>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find all irreducible polynomials of degree 1, 2 and 4 over <m>\F_2</m>, and show that their product is <m>x^{16}-x</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Show that <m>d</m> divides <m>n</m> if and only if <m>x^d - 1</m> divides <m>x^n - 1</m>. Further show that <m>\F_{p^d}\subseteq\F_{p^n}</m> if and only if <m>d</m> divides <m>n</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>p</m> be a prime and let <m>0\neq a\in\F_p</m>. Show that <m>x^p - x + a</m> is irreducible and separable over <m>\F_p</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>K</m> is a field and that it is not a perfect field. Prove that there exist irreducible inseparable polynomials over <m>K</m>. Conclude that there exist inseparable finite extensions of <m>K</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>K/F</m> be  field extension, and let <m>F</m> be a perfect field. Suppose that <m>f(x)\in F[x]</m> has no repeated irreducible factors in <m>F[x]</m>. Show that <m>f(x)</m> has no repeated irreducible factors in <m>K[x]</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>